1
00:00:02,616 --> 00:00:06,049
[♪]

2
00:01:02,116 --> 00:01:03,882
<i>[WOMAN SINGING ELEGANTLY]</i>

3
00:01:10,249 --> 00:01:12,182
[PEOPLE CHATTING]

4
00:01:13,049 --> 00:01:15,216
Where did he go?

5
00:01:15,249 --> 00:01:16,916
This is Delta, Block D5.

6
00:01:16,949 --> 00:01:18,216
No sign of Klaus.

7
00:01:18,249 --> 00:01:19,216
Hurry!

8
00:01:19,249 --> 00:01:21,749
Before he leaves the station.

9
00:01:24,216 --> 00:01:25,816
Uh!
Oh.

10
00:01:25,849 --> 00:01:26,582
Hey!

11
00:01:31,216 --> 00:01:34,082
A3. The subject's
heading towards A3.

12
00:01:34,116 --> 00:01:36,682
TAWASHI:
We can't let him get away.

13
00:01:39,982 --> 00:01:41,016
Oh! Klaus!

14
00:01:45,616 --> 00:01:47,216
Goodbye.

15
00:01:47,249 --> 00:01:48,216
Huh?

16
00:01:48,249 --> 00:01:49,549
Hold it right there, Klaus.

17
00:01:49,582 --> 00:01:50,982
Ah! Somebody
come quick!

18
00:01:51,016 --> 00:01:53,149
A robot's about to shoot
a human.

19
00:01:53,182 --> 00:01:54,982
Stop him!

20
00:01:57,249 --> 00:01:59,816
You have it all wrong. We were
chasing a robot, not a human.

21
00:01:59,849 --> 00:02:02,016
Well, I think I know a man
when I see one.

22
00:02:02,049 --> 00:02:03,016
Yeah, I saw him too.

23
00:02:03,049 --> 00:02:05,982
Definitely not a robot.

24
00:02:06,016 --> 00:02:08,649
ASTRO:
<i>Klaus may look like a human,</i>

25
00:02:08,682 --> 00:02:09,749
<i>but he's not.</i>

26
00:02:09,782 --> 00:02:12,116
<i>He's really an undercover</i>
<i>police robot</i>

27
00:02:12,149 --> 00:02:14,849
<i>programmed to look and act</i>
<i>just like a human.</i>

28
00:02:16,182 --> 00:02:18,049
<i>Twelve hours ago,</i>

29
00:02:18,082 --> 00:02:20,882
<i>he was considered one of</i>
<i>the best undercover agents.</i>

30
00:02:20,916 --> 00:02:22,782
MAN:
The plan is foolproof.

31
00:02:22,816 --> 00:02:25,682
I set up a fake account
here at Burlane Corporation

32
00:02:25,716 --> 00:02:28,449
so we can sell Hyper-IC
on the black market.

33
00:02:28,482 --> 00:02:31,449
And don't worry,
you'll be well compensated.

34
00:02:31,482 --> 00:02:34,482
Thank you, Mr. Robin.
You're much too generous.

35
00:02:34,516 --> 00:02:36,749
So when can I see
the new Hyper-IC?

36
00:02:36,782 --> 00:02:39,582
Give me a sec.

37
00:02:46,882 --> 00:02:49,116
ROBIN: It's amazing how
such a tiny little device

38
00:02:49,149 --> 00:02:51,549
is the key to producing weapons.

39
00:02:53,549 --> 00:02:55,482
Honestly, when you first joined
the company,

40
00:02:55,516 --> 00:02:57,049
I had my doubts about you.

41
00:02:57,082 --> 00:02:58,982
I actually thought
you were a cop.

42
00:02:59,016 --> 00:03:00,682
[LAUGHING]

43
00:03:02,249 --> 00:03:04,016
Here's the latest version
of the--

44
00:03:04,049 --> 00:03:05,182
Hmm?

45
00:03:09,682 --> 00:03:12,449
KLAUS: The man you're looking
for is Cornelius Robin,

46
00:03:12,482 --> 00:03:13,816
divisional vice president
of sales.

47
00:03:13,849 --> 00:03:15,649
MAN:
<i>Sales, we should have known.</i>

48
00:03:15,682 --> 00:03:18,982
I'll transmit
all the necessary evidence now.

49
00:03:19,016 --> 00:03:21,082
<i>Roger that. We'll see you</i>
<i>back at the station.</i>

50
00:03:21,116 --> 00:03:22,082
<i>There's a zipcar</i>
<i>waiting for you.</i>

51
00:03:22,116 --> 00:03:23,782
Okay.

52
00:03:23,816 --> 00:03:26,949
<i>Klaus, nice work</i>
<i>on your final assignment.</i>

53
00:03:31,982 --> 00:03:34,149
MAN: Klaus just left
Burlane Corporation.

54
00:03:37,016 --> 00:03:39,882
It's impressive that he managed
to get so close to Robin.

55
00:03:39,916 --> 00:03:41,182
Data's in.

56
00:03:41,216 --> 00:03:43,116
Send out a team
to pick up Robin.

57
00:03:43,149 --> 00:03:44,482
And don't forget
to read him his rights.

58
00:04:04,782 --> 00:04:08,016
[MAN HUMMING]

59
00:04:08,049 --> 00:04:10,116
Hmm? Huh?

60
00:04:10,149 --> 00:04:11,982
Hey there, Klaus.

61
00:04:12,016 --> 00:04:13,449
Oh?

62
00:04:19,716 --> 00:04:21,616
What?

63
00:04:21,649 --> 00:04:23,016
Klaus's transmitter
just went dead.

64
00:04:23,049 --> 00:04:24,149
What is he doing?

65
00:04:24,182 --> 00:04:25,116
Klaus!

66
00:04:35,182 --> 00:04:37,449
MAN: We've got a serious
problem here.

67
00:04:37,482 --> 00:04:39,816
One of our police robots
has disappeared.

68
00:04:39,849 --> 00:04:42,149
This is all
your fault, Cutter!

69
00:04:42,182 --> 00:04:44,882
Klaus was
your responsibility!

70
00:04:44,916 --> 00:04:48,582
From now on, Detective Tawashi
will lead the investigation.

71
00:04:48,616 --> 00:04:50,182
Dr. O'Shay and Astro

72
00:04:50,216 --> 00:04:52,049
will continue to assist
in the search.

73
00:04:52,082 --> 00:04:54,849
Don't you think we're being
a bit overdramatic, Chief?

74
00:04:54,882 --> 00:04:56,682
What if I said,
by tomorrow night

75
00:04:56,716 --> 00:04:59,182
we wouldn't have to worry
about Klaus ever again?

76
00:04:59,216 --> 00:05:00,916
What do you mean by that?

77
00:05:00,949 --> 00:05:02,716
I planted a failsafe protocol

78
00:05:02,749 --> 00:05:04,916
in every undercover
humanoid robot

79
00:05:04,949 --> 00:05:06,616
to prevent them
from running away.

80
00:05:06,649 --> 00:05:08,749
When a robot cuts off
its digital locator,

81
00:05:08,782 --> 00:05:10,216
a virus is introduced
into its system.

82
00:05:10,249 --> 00:05:12,016
If it doesn't turn itself in
within 24 hours,

83
00:05:12,049 --> 00:05:13,016
it'll shut down.

84
00:05:13,049 --> 00:05:14,882
Huh?
Permanently.

85
00:05:14,916 --> 00:05:17,516
Of course, Klaus knows
full well about the virus.

86
00:05:17,549 --> 00:05:18,982
This is outrageous!

87
00:05:19,016 --> 00:05:19,916
What gives you the right

88
00:05:19,949 --> 00:05:22,982
to go around implanting
robots with viruses?

89
00:05:23,016 --> 00:05:25,749
Especially ones like Klaus,
who have hearts and emotions?

90
00:05:25,782 --> 00:05:27,682
That was
a big mistake, doctor.

91
00:05:27,716 --> 00:05:28,882
What's that mean?

92
00:05:28,916 --> 00:05:30,882
That's the problem,
his heart.

93
00:05:30,916 --> 00:05:32,949
He grew too close
to the people around him.

94
00:05:32,982 --> 00:05:34,549
He got attached
to human comforts.

95
00:05:34,582 --> 00:05:36,782
So much so that he
wants to be human!

96
00:05:36,816 --> 00:05:38,682
[GROANING]

97
00:05:38,716 --> 00:05:41,016
Hmm.

98
00:05:42,482 --> 00:05:44,216
O'SHAY:
We have to find Klaus

99
00:05:44,249 --> 00:05:46,082
before the virus spreads
to his central processor.

100
00:05:46,116 --> 00:05:47,482
If we're not too late,

101
00:05:47,516 --> 00:05:49,449
this microchip
should counteract the virus.

102
00:05:49,482 --> 00:05:51,649
Okay, got it.

103
00:05:51,682 --> 00:05:54,049
Astro, I'm sure Klaus had
a good reason for running away

104
00:05:54,082 --> 00:05:55,116
yesterday afternoon.

105
00:05:55,149 --> 00:05:56,449
I know he does.

106
00:05:59,682 --> 00:06:01,449
MAN: No one's seen
or heard from him.

107
00:06:01,482 --> 00:06:02,882
He didn't even pack a bag.

108
00:06:02,916 --> 00:06:04,682
And no clues in his house
indicating where he went.

109
00:06:04,716 --> 00:06:06,616
If we can't figure out
where he's going,

110
00:06:06,649 --> 00:06:08,782
we can still find out
where he's coming from.

111
00:06:08,816 --> 00:06:12,216
Delta, I need you and Astro
to go over Klaus's steps

112
00:06:12,249 --> 00:06:13,549
right before he disappeared.

113
00:06:13,582 --> 00:06:15,082
Yes, sir.

114
00:06:15,116 --> 00:06:16,416
Great! Partners!

115
00:06:17,749 --> 00:06:20,516
[GROANS]

116
00:06:20,549 --> 00:06:22,716
Astro,
just so you know,

117
00:06:22,749 --> 00:06:24,616
I have no intention
on saving Klaus.

118
00:06:24,649 --> 00:06:25,549
Why not?

119
00:06:25,582 --> 00:06:28,649
You guys were both
in the police department.

120
00:06:28,682 --> 00:06:30,516
Weren't you,
Delta?

121
00:06:30,549 --> 00:06:32,749
That's exactly why
I can't forgive him!

122
00:06:32,782 --> 00:06:33,616
Huh?

123
00:06:33,649 --> 00:06:36,716
We may be able
to think for ourselves,

124
00:06:36,749 --> 00:06:38,949
but our prime directive
is to uphold the law.

125
00:06:38,982 --> 00:06:41,916
It took years for police robots
to earn the people's trust.

126
00:06:41,949 --> 00:06:44,716
By running out on us,
Klaus makes us all look bad.

127
00:06:44,749 --> 00:06:46,616
Well, I'm sure Klaus can
explain why he did--

128
00:06:46,649 --> 00:06:51,116
Astro, there's no excuse for a
police robot to disobey orders.

129
00:06:51,149 --> 00:06:52,616
Ugh! Delta!

130
00:06:59,749 --> 00:07:00,982
Goodbye.

131
00:07:02,949 --> 00:07:05,449
ASTRO: <i>I'm the only one left</i>
<i>on Klaus's side.</i>

132
00:07:05,482 --> 00:07:08,482
<i>I've got to save him.</i>

133
00:07:15,232 --> 00:07:17,432
This is where the zipcar
was supposed to get Klaus

134
00:07:17,465 --> 00:07:19,098
after he left
Burlane Corporation.

135
00:07:19,132 --> 00:07:21,232
Very nice. So, what about it?

136
00:07:21,265 --> 00:07:23,865
Well, maybe something
happened to him here.

137
00:07:23,898 --> 00:07:26,898
Maybe he was forced to run away.

138
00:07:28,998 --> 00:07:30,565
You're reading
way too much into this.

139
00:07:30,598 --> 00:07:32,498
Let's go.

140
00:07:32,532 --> 00:07:34,865
I know where we can find one of
his undercover android friends.

141
00:07:39,232 --> 00:07:40,198
[GROANS]

142
00:07:40,232 --> 00:07:42,065
Huh?

143
00:07:42,098 --> 00:07:43,532
FEMALE VOICE:
<i>And so the young man</i>

144
00:07:43,565 --> 00:07:45,298
<i>was cursed</i>
<i>by the evil sorcerer.</i>

145
00:07:45,332 --> 00:07:47,598
<i>But this was not the end</i>
<i>of his journey.</i>

146
00:07:47,632 --> 00:07:49,298
<i>It was only the beginning.</i>

147
00:07:49,332 --> 00:07:51,265
<i>In order to bring back</i>
<i>his precious memories...</i>

148
00:07:51,298 --> 00:07:53,032
[MOANS]

149
00:07:59,665 --> 00:08:01,832
[BEAUTIFUL OPERA MUSIC PLAYING]

150
00:08:10,465 --> 00:08:13,932
Klaus was the best undercover
robot I had ever seen.

151
00:08:13,965 --> 00:08:16,965
I was honored to have
trained him myself.

152
00:08:19,398 --> 00:08:22,098
After their police training,
the undercover robots

153
00:08:22,132 --> 00:08:24,398
spend four weeks
living with their instructors

154
00:08:24,432 --> 00:08:29,098
so they can learn the everyday
details of human life.

155
00:08:29,132 --> 00:08:31,065
So he spent some time here
in this mansion?

156
00:08:31,098 --> 00:08:33,298
Yes.

157
00:08:33,332 --> 00:08:36,865
But unlike the others,
Klaus was a different breed.

158
00:08:36,898 --> 00:08:37,832
I'm gonna need
more than that.

159
00:08:39,498 --> 00:08:43,098
It was uncanny. I actually began
to think he was human.

160
00:08:43,132 --> 00:08:46,065
Did you just say
what I think you just said?

161
00:08:46,098 --> 00:08:47,065
FEMALE VOICE:
I've been working undercover

162
00:08:47,098 --> 00:08:49,065
as a human for three years.

163
00:08:49,098 --> 00:08:50,198
ASTRO:
Do you like pretending?

164
00:08:50,232 --> 00:08:52,598
Well, I don't know if "like"
is how I would describe it.

165
00:08:52,632 --> 00:08:54,465
This might sound strange,

166
00:08:54,498 --> 00:08:57,132
but I spend so much time
living with humans,

167
00:08:57,165 --> 00:08:59,165
that sometimes I forget
that I'm a robot.

168
00:09:02,032 --> 00:09:03,998
Was Klaus like that also?

169
00:09:04,032 --> 00:09:05,865
I really
don't know.

170
00:09:05,898 --> 00:09:07,198
But when no one
was around,

171
00:09:07,232 --> 00:09:09,365
Klaus liked to come here
to listen to music.

172
00:09:09,398 --> 00:09:10,598
To music?

173
00:09:10,632 --> 00:09:11,998
Yes.

174
00:09:12,032 --> 00:09:13,165
All undercover robots
are programmed

175
00:09:13,198 --> 00:09:16,432
to understand everything from
music theory and art history

176
00:09:16,465 --> 00:09:18,298
to famous literary works.

177
00:09:18,332 --> 00:09:20,132
It is essential
to their success

178
00:09:20,165 --> 00:09:22,032
that they appear human
in every way possible.

179
00:09:22,065 --> 00:09:24,432
However...

180
00:09:24,465 --> 00:09:27,432
<i>Klaus was different.</i>

181
00:09:27,465 --> 00:09:29,432
Would you mind if I listened
to that piece again,

182
00:09:29,465 --> 00:09:30,598
Professor Salsed?

183
00:09:30,632 --> 00:09:32,165
Not at all.

184
00:09:32,198 --> 00:09:34,898
But it should be stored
in your memory files.

185
00:09:34,932 --> 00:09:37,932
It is, but it's not quite the
same when I play it in my head.

186
00:09:39,565 --> 00:09:42,498
You can actually appreciate
the difference between the two?

187
00:09:42,532 --> 00:09:43,832
Sure.

188
00:09:45,632 --> 00:09:48,198
[BEAUTIFUL OPERA MUSIC PLAYING]

189
00:09:48,232 --> 00:09:49,965
[SINGING ALONG]

190
00:09:49,998 --> 00:09:51,365
Huh?

191
00:09:51,398 --> 00:09:54,465
SALSED: <i>Klaus's development</i>
<i>was not limited to just music.</i>

192
00:09:54,498 --> 00:09:56,398
He also developed

193
00:09:56,432 --> 00:09:59,398
a sense of family with myself
and my granddaughter Michelle.

194
00:09:59,432 --> 00:10:00,998
Is that her?
Yes.

195
00:10:01,032 --> 00:10:02,932
Her parents
both work on the moon,

196
00:10:02,965 --> 00:10:05,132
so she doesn't see them
very often.

197
00:10:05,165 --> 00:10:07,032
Klaus may have only lived here
a short time,

198
00:10:07,065 --> 00:10:08,898
but he was like a father to her.

199
00:10:08,932 --> 00:10:11,498
It's a shame that after
his latest assignment

200
00:10:11,532 --> 00:10:12,965
with Burlane Corporation,

201
00:10:12,998 --> 00:10:14,165
he was scheduled to be upgraded.

202
00:10:14,198 --> 00:10:15,165
What?

203
00:10:15,198 --> 00:10:17,232
Did you say upgraded?

204
00:10:17,265 --> 00:10:18,532
Cutter didn't tell you?

205
00:10:18,565 --> 00:10:20,132
It was all set
for today.

206
00:10:20,165 --> 00:10:22,498
So? I get awesome upgrades
all the time.

207
00:10:22,532 --> 00:10:23,865
They make me faster
and stronger.

208
00:10:23,898 --> 00:10:26,065
This was a complete
system upgrade.

209
00:10:26,098 --> 00:10:28,232
His personality and memories
would be erased.

210
00:10:28,265 --> 00:10:29,865
Now it makes
total sense.

211
00:10:29,898 --> 00:10:33,232
So in order to escape
being upgraded, Klaus fled.

212
00:10:33,265 --> 00:10:35,332
Actually, he agreed
to have the upgrade.

213
00:10:35,365 --> 00:10:36,332
Huh?

214
00:10:36,365 --> 00:10:37,332
I don't buy it!

215
00:10:37,365 --> 00:10:38,998
It's true, Delta.

216
00:10:39,032 --> 00:10:41,132
That's why he left
this record with me.

217
00:10:41,165 --> 00:10:43,398
It was given to him
by his instructor.

218
00:10:43,432 --> 00:10:45,465
It was very special to him.

219
00:10:45,498 --> 00:10:47,965
I remember it
like it was yesterday.

220
00:10:47,998 --> 00:10:52,565
[BEAUTIFUL OPERA MUSIC PLAYING]

221
00:10:57,665 --> 00:11:00,165
You're leaving behind
your favorite album?

222
00:11:00,198 --> 00:11:03,465
For you. It means a lot to me,
and I want you to have it.

223
00:11:03,498 --> 00:11:04,532
Why?

224
00:11:06,165 --> 00:11:10,265
The new Klaus won't
appreciate it like I do.

225
00:11:10,298 --> 00:11:12,598
I don't understand
why you have to be upgraded.

226
00:11:12,632 --> 00:11:13,998
You're already the best we have.

227
00:11:14,032 --> 00:11:16,365
So what if you
listen to music?

228
00:11:16,398 --> 00:11:17,898
So what if you
made friends?

229
00:11:17,932 --> 00:11:19,198
Isn't that
what they wanted?

230
00:11:19,232 --> 00:11:21,165
For us to be as human
as possible?

231
00:11:21,198 --> 00:11:23,398
Why are they so afraid
of you, Klaus?

232
00:11:23,432 --> 00:11:24,965
They just are,

233
00:11:24,998 --> 00:11:26,165
and an order's
an order.

234
00:11:26,198 --> 00:11:27,398
But, Klaus...

235
00:11:31,465 --> 00:11:35,098
Remember me every time
you listen to that song.

236
00:11:35,132 --> 00:11:37,165
All that Klaus
ever wanted

237
00:11:37,198 --> 00:11:39,398
was to be the best
humanoid undercover agent.

238
00:11:39,432 --> 00:11:41,465
Yes, but he still
disobeyed orders!

239
00:11:41,498 --> 00:11:43,065
And that's a fact.

240
00:11:45,532 --> 00:11:48,165
Do you have any idea
what could've changed his mind?

241
00:11:48,198 --> 00:11:50,898
No, I don't,
I'm sorry.

242
00:11:51,998 --> 00:11:53,465
Who is this woman?

243
00:11:53,498 --> 00:11:54,898
That's Leah Jade,

244
00:11:54,932 --> 00:11:56,598
an opera singer
from Xenon.

245
00:11:56,632 --> 00:11:59,465
Her world tour begins...
any day now.

246
00:11:59,498 --> 00:12:00,565
Let me check.

247
00:12:00,598 --> 00:12:03,398
Actually, it's starting today.

248
00:12:03,432 --> 00:12:05,098
Can you see where
today's show is?

249
00:12:05,132 --> 00:12:06,498
It's in Wayland.

250
00:12:06,532 --> 00:12:08,232
Wayland, huh?

251
00:12:08,265 --> 00:12:09,632
Hmm.

252
00:12:09,665 --> 00:12:10,865
Oh!

253
00:12:10,898 --> 00:12:12,998
Astro! Where are you going?

254
00:12:21,565 --> 00:12:24,132
Listen up.
Klaus is obsessed with Jade.

255
00:12:24,165 --> 00:12:26,298
I know he's at this concert.
Now find him!

256
00:12:37,232 --> 00:12:38,232
Huh?

257
00:12:38,265 --> 00:12:40,432
Klaus. Follow me.

258
00:12:40,465 --> 00:12:41,998
Hurry.

259
00:12:43,298 --> 00:12:45,065
Hey, you all right?

260
00:12:45,098 --> 00:12:46,265
No.

261
00:12:46,298 --> 00:12:49,298
My systems are starting
to fail. Ugh!

262
00:12:49,332 --> 00:12:52,165
Hang on. We need to install
this microchip right away.

263
00:12:52,198 --> 00:12:53,398
Oh!

264
00:12:53,432 --> 00:12:54,332
Hold it right there.

265
00:13:01,070 --> 00:13:03,003
This is between
you and me, Cutter.

266
00:13:03,037 --> 00:13:04,170
Leave these two
out of it.

267
00:13:04,203 --> 00:13:06,337
Arggh!
Klaus.

268
00:13:06,370 --> 00:13:08,603
A robot
giving orders to a human.

269
00:13:08,637 --> 00:13:10,537
Your love for music
was just the start.

270
00:13:10,570 --> 00:13:12,470
He's not giving orders.

271
00:13:12,503 --> 00:13:14,437
He's just trying
to protect his friends.

272
00:13:14,470 --> 00:13:16,637
There's no law
against listening to music!

273
00:13:17,703 --> 00:13:19,337
[LAUGHING]

274
00:13:19,370 --> 00:13:20,503
Huh?

275
00:13:20,537 --> 00:13:22,570
You're so naive, Astro.

276
00:13:22,603 --> 00:13:24,037
It's not just the music,

277
00:13:24,070 --> 00:13:25,670
it's the art,
the books, the jobs,

278
00:13:25,703 --> 00:13:27,303
it's everything
that belongs to humankind.

279
00:13:27,337 --> 00:13:31,137
Robots were built to make
the lives of humans easier.

280
00:13:31,170 --> 00:13:33,703
Instead, you're taking away
everything that's sacred to us.

281
00:13:33,737 --> 00:13:35,670
Giving you hearts and emotions
was the last straw,

282
00:13:35,703 --> 00:13:37,303
and I won't take it anymore!

283
00:13:37,337 --> 00:13:39,537
Even if it means
eliminating you all myself!

284
00:13:39,570 --> 00:13:40,737
That's crazy.

285
00:13:40,770 --> 00:13:41,737
Robots are
your friends--

286
00:13:41,770 --> 00:13:42,737
Arggh!
Klaus.

287
00:13:42,770 --> 00:13:44,137
CUTTER:
Delta!

288
00:13:44,170 --> 00:13:46,070
Bring the fugitive to me.

289
00:13:46,103 --> 00:13:47,203
That is an order!

290
00:13:47,237 --> 00:13:48,603
If you don't bring him now,

291
00:13:48,637 --> 00:13:49,603
I'll destroy you too.

292
00:13:49,637 --> 00:13:50,603
Delta.

293
00:13:50,637 --> 00:13:52,570
Game's over, Astro.

294
00:13:52,603 --> 00:13:55,270
Commissioned police robots
have to follow every order.

295
00:13:55,303 --> 00:13:56,470
Huh?

296
00:13:56,503 --> 00:13:57,470
Well, you see,

297
00:13:57,503 --> 00:13:59,670
you're no longer
in charge of this case, Cutter,

298
00:13:59,703 --> 00:14:01,570
so I'm no longer required
to follow your orders.

299
00:14:03,337 --> 00:14:04,503
Harggh!

300
00:14:04,537 --> 00:14:06,103
Whoa!

301
00:14:13,737 --> 00:14:16,303
Are you okay, Astro?
Yeah.

302
00:14:16,337 --> 00:14:18,070
Let's rocket!

303
00:14:22,570 --> 00:14:23,970
Hold on, Klaus.

304
00:14:24,003 --> 00:14:25,637
Let me install
the antivirus.

305
00:14:25,670 --> 00:14:27,303
Hurry up.
They'll be here soon.

306
00:14:35,503 --> 00:14:36,437
Thank you, Astro.

307
00:14:36,470 --> 00:14:37,637
Klaus.

308
00:14:37,670 --> 00:14:39,337
So why did you
run away?

309
00:14:39,370 --> 00:14:44,503
Well...I was fully prepared
to have the upgrade.

310
00:14:44,537 --> 00:14:47,203
<i>I was about to return</i>
<i>to the police station</i>

311
00:14:47,237 --> 00:14:48,970
<i>after the Burlane</i>
<i>Corporation mission.</i>

312
00:14:49,003 --> 00:14:52,137
<i>But then I heard something.</i>

313
00:14:52,170 --> 00:14:53,137
Huh?

314
00:14:53,170 --> 00:14:55,537
[BEAUTIFUL OPERA MUSIC PLAYING]

315
00:15:04,503 --> 00:15:06,470
Leah Jade.

316
00:15:06,503 --> 00:15:08,103
<i>When I saw</i>
<i>she was performing live,</i>

317
00:15:08,137 --> 00:15:09,503
<i>I had to see her just once.</i>

318
00:15:09,537 --> 00:15:12,203
I know that may sound
strange to you.

319
00:15:12,237 --> 00:15:13,070
No. Huh?

320
00:15:16,370 --> 00:15:18,003
DELTA:
It's the police...

321
00:15:18,037 --> 00:15:19,503
in combat suits.

322
00:15:19,537 --> 00:15:21,737
Take them all down!

323
00:15:21,770 --> 00:15:23,603
And don't sweat it.
They're robots.

324
00:15:23,637 --> 00:15:24,703
They can't shoot us.

325
00:15:30,470 --> 00:15:32,337
Arggh!

326
00:15:32,370 --> 00:15:34,970
Delta, aim for the shoulder pin.
They won't be hurt.

327
00:15:36,503 --> 00:15:38,970
Arggh!

328
00:15:48,070 --> 00:15:49,437
ASTRO:
This way.

329
00:16:00,270 --> 00:16:01,203
ANNOUNCER:
<i>Ladies and gentlemen,</i>

330
00:16:01,237 --> 00:16:04,037
<i>Leah Jade.</i>

331
00:16:07,003 --> 00:16:08,937
No, Klaus.

332
00:16:11,370 --> 00:16:12,337
Ahh!

333
00:16:12,370 --> 00:16:13,337
Delta!

334
00:16:13,370 --> 00:16:14,970
[GRUNTS]

335
00:16:17,670 --> 00:16:19,070
KLAUS:
That's it.

336
00:16:24,303 --> 00:16:25,703
Let's go.

337
00:16:25,737 --> 00:16:28,303
[CROWD APPLAUDS & CHEERS]

338
00:16:31,470 --> 00:16:34,203
[SINGING BEAUTIFUL OPERA SONG]

339
00:16:54,703 --> 00:16:55,970
KLAUS:
<i>Delta.</i>

340
00:16:56,003 --> 00:16:58,703
<i>Now do you understand</i>
<i>why some humans hate robots?</i>

341
00:17:00,270 --> 00:17:02,203
DELTA:
<i>Because we're different.</i>

342
00:17:02,237 --> 00:17:03,270
<i>Because we're stronger!</i>

343
00:17:03,303 --> 00:17:05,703
<i>Because we can do things</i>
<i>they cannot.</i>

344
00:17:05,737 --> 00:17:07,670
KLAUS: <i>We may be made</i>
<i>out of machinery,</i>

345
00:17:07,703 --> 00:17:10,270
<i>but we can still think</i>
<i>for ourselves.</i>

346
00:17:10,303 --> 00:17:11,937
<i>And many of us</i>
<i>have feelings too.</i>

347
00:17:14,637 --> 00:17:19,103
ASTRO: <i>Maybe they're not afraid</i>
<i>because we're different.</i>

348
00:17:19,137 --> 00:17:22,637
<i>Maybe they're afraid</i>
<i>because...we're the same.</i>

349
00:17:29,570 --> 00:17:31,537
You might be right, Astro.

350
00:17:31,570 --> 00:17:34,603
So why build us that way?

351
00:17:36,270 --> 00:17:38,637
It's the end of
the road, Klaus. Huh?

352
00:17:38,670 --> 00:17:41,270
DELTA: Klaus, I just have
one question for you.

353
00:17:43,170 --> 00:17:46,370
Did you ever
actually want to be human?

354
00:17:46,403 --> 00:17:49,503
I can honestly say
I never wanted to be a human.

355
00:17:49,537 --> 00:17:52,670
The only thing I ever
really wanted was to be me.

356
00:17:52,703 --> 00:17:54,037
Weapons up!

357
00:17:55,637 --> 00:17:56,603
Ah!

358
00:17:56,637 --> 00:17:58,570
No. Klaus!

359
00:17:58,603 --> 00:18:02,503
Delta, you're a good officer.
Don't ever forget that.

360
00:18:02,537 --> 00:18:05,270
Just stay true to yourself.

361
00:18:05,303 --> 00:18:06,637
Wait!

362
00:18:06,670 --> 00:18:07,937
Fire!

363
00:18:11,770 --> 00:18:13,070
Arggh!

364
00:18:14,337 --> 00:18:15,437
Arggh!

365
00:18:15,470 --> 00:18:16,703
What?

366
00:18:18,403 --> 00:18:20,003
[ALL SCREAMING]

367
00:18:26,470 --> 00:18:28,037
Klaus.

368
00:18:28,070 --> 00:18:29,603
You're scrap metal!

369
00:18:31,603 --> 00:18:32,970
Oww!

370
00:18:33,003 --> 00:18:34,437
TAWASHI:
<i>Drop your weapons.</i>

371
00:18:37,637 --> 00:18:38,737
Tawashi?

372
00:18:38,770 --> 00:18:40,337
Right now!

373
00:18:40,370 --> 00:18:42,303
I'm not a robot,
so I will take you down.

374
00:18:42,337 --> 00:18:44,170
[GRUNTS]

375
00:18:51,070 --> 00:18:52,670
ANDO:
We never found Klaus's body.

376
00:18:52,703 --> 00:18:54,970
TAWASHI: Well, he couldn't
have survived that fall.

377
00:18:55,003 --> 00:18:57,603
The current must've washed
his parts out to sea.

378
00:18:59,603 --> 00:19:02,003
Delta, I've got
something to show you.

379
00:19:02,037 --> 00:19:04,237
Later, Astro,
I'm on duty right now.

380
00:19:04,270 --> 00:19:07,637
I promise it'll only take
a split second.

381
00:19:09,637 --> 00:19:11,737
Klaus is alive!

382
00:19:11,770 --> 00:19:13,970
What did you just say?

383
00:19:14,003 --> 00:19:16,470
BOTH:
Nothing, detective.

384
00:19:16,503 --> 00:19:18,337
Hmm.

385
00:19:42,737 --> 00:19:45,003
[BIRD SQUAWKS]

386
00:19:50,570 --> 00:19:53,237
[♪]

